<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: CAMARILLO; COUNCIL TO CONSIDER DAWSON-PETIT SIGNAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By J. E. MITCHELL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In an attempt to ease rush-hour congestion through a southeast Camarillo 
intersection, the City Council tonight will consider spending nearly $85,000 to 
install a signal at the site. 
</P>
<P>
 The signal light, if approved by the council, will be installed at the 
intersection of Dawson Drive and Petit Street, said city traffic engineer Tom 
Fox. 
</P>
<P>
 "We have frustrated motorists ducking through neighborhood side streets to get 
around the tie-ups," Fox said. "We hope the new light will ease the congestion 
and cut back on the traffic flowing through the nearby neighborhoods." 
</P>
<P>
 Fox said Ventura-based Taft Electric Co. submitted the lowest bid at $84,738, 
and the city engineer's staff has recommended that the company get the 
contract. If approved by the council, construction will start within the month, 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 The council will meet at 5 p.m. at City Hall, 601 Carmen Drive. J. E. MITCHELL 
</P>
</TEXT>
