<HEADLINE>
<P>
CONTRACTORS FINED OVER SUBWAY WORK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A sweeping inspection of Metro Rail subway construction conditions found 131 
alleged health and safety violations that together carry fines of more than 
$250,000, according to a final report Tuesday released by Cal/OSHA. 
</P>
<P>
 In a joint weeklong audit by state and federal occupational safety agencies 
last month, inspectors reported inadequate shoring around trenches and numerous 
electrical hazards. 
</P>
<P>
 They also found numerous cigarette butts in a tunnel that must be continuously 
monitored for methane and hydrogen sulfide -- both highly combustible gases. 
</P>
<P>
 The penalties total $288,470, more than half of that ($164,000) attributed to 
Shea-Kiewit-Kenny, one of the subway project's biggest contractors. 
Tutor-Salibi-Perini, another major Metro Rail contractor, was ordered to pay 
$59,000. The firms can appeal the fines. 
</P>
