<P>
WEST VALLEY FOCUS: CHATSWORTH; CITY APPROVES PACT FOR BANK PROJECT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By HUGO MARTIN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Los Angeles City Council approved a development agreement Tuesday to 
ensure that Great Western Bank can complete the development of its headquarters 
in Chatsworth. 
</P>
<P>
 The agreement guarantees that the bank can finish building the mixed-use 
project regardless of any changes the city may make in neighborhood zoning laws 
over the next 10 years or so, according to city officials and bank 
representatives. 
</P>
<P>
 About five years ago, Great Western began development of 790,000 square feet 
of office space, a 90,000-square-foot employee service center, a child-care 
center for 300 children and parking space for the entire complex on Prairie 
Street near Oakdale Avenue. 
</P>
<P>
 The bank has yet to build three six-story office buildings and garages for 
most of its parking, said Jerry Welch, Great Western's manager for corporate 
services. 
</P>
<P>
 The bank has not set a date for completing the project. Consequently, the bank 
asked the city to approve the development agreement to guarantee that the 
remainder of the complex can be built regardless of future changes in the 
area's zoning codes, Welch said. HUGO MARTIN 
</P>
</TEXT>
